"about 1265":"about 1265","1319":"1319","La Haye-Pesnel, Avranches, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"La Haye-Pesnel, Manche, Normandy, France","France":"France","Courcy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Courcy, Calvados, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"COURCY","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Andree, Jacques, Michel, Monique.","French: habitational name from any of the places in Calvados, Loiret, Manche, and Marne called Courcy.","History: Nicolas Lemière <i>dit</i> Courcy from Courcy in Manche, France, married Louise-Geneviève Dubé in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1749."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Janne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Johanna ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hanna","meanings":["Either the biblical name (  see  <b>Hannah</b>   ) or a short form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]},{"name":"Philippa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Philip .  In England during the Middle Ages the vernacular name <i>Philip</i> was borne by women as well as men, but female bearers were distinguished in Latin records by this form. It was not, however, used as a regular given name until the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Janne Philippa de COURCY was born in 1228, in Courcy, Calvados, Normandy, France, her father, Richard II de Courcy, was 35 and her mother, Mathilde du Hommet, was 26. She had at least 3 sons and 3 daughters with Guillaume IV de PAYNEL Baron de Hambye seigneur de Bréhal et Drax. She died in France."},"et":{"1228–":"1228–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1215–1272":"1215–1272","1250–1295":"1250–1295","1250–1319":"1250–1319","1256–Male":"1256